b. instruct the Inventory Committee to:
i. reconstitute with an adequate number of members who can perform the assigned duties and responsibilities, and thereafter devise the PIP for the conduct of physical inventory of all PPE at the most reasonable time, including the preparation of RPCPPE with its pertinent property records and submit a copy of the same to the AT not later than January 31 of each year. The RPCPPE shall be reconciled with the PPE records or ledger maintained by the MAO and any discrepancy should be adjusted accordingly; and
ii. conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE in close coordination with the General Service Office and the MAO to establish the veracity and propriety of the balances of PPE accounts; and
c. require the Storekeeper to:
i. prepare the corresponding Inventory and Inspection Report for unserviceable identified properties that remained recorded in the books, and initiate the process of disposing the same;
ii. maintain efficient property management by following the prescribed procedures in property recording and maintaining accurate property cards (PCs);
iii. ensure that the Property Acknowledgement Receipts (PARs) are prepared, issued to end-users, and regularly updated/renewed every three years;
iv. assign property tags/reference numbers for each PPE item during the physical inventory count to easily identify and trace the location of the subject PPE; and
v. undergo training on supply and property management to keep abreast and broaden his understanding of his responsibilities and accountabilities on property management; and
d. order the Municipal Treasurer (MT) to:
i. apply and/or renew the registration of all serviceable motor vehicles with the LTO and contracts of insurance from the GSIS to avoid additional expenses in terms of penalties and payment of damages to third-party liabilities in case of vehicular accident or other casualty;
ii. monitor regularly if those serviceable motor vehicles are renewed yearly with the LTO and have appropriate insurance coverage from the GSIS; and
iii. refund the ₱15,476.00 representing penalty and charges on delinquent registration of serviceable motor vehicles to LTO.

We recommended that Management direct the ME, the MPDC, and the LDC to: (i) submit an explanation for the non-implementation of the development projects in accordance with the development plans and targets for the year; (ii) regularly monitor the status of implementation so that necessary interventions or rectification may be introduced at the earliest possible time; and (iii) strictly abide with the target project timelines for the future projects to maximize the developmental benefits and the early enjoyment thereof by the intended beneficiaries;
b. enjoin the ME to require the posting of the warranty security by the contractor before the issuance of the Certificate of Final Acceptance pursuant to Section 62.2.2 of the RIRR of R.A. No. 9184 and thereafter only issue the Certificate of Final Acceptance after the defects liability period to maximize the period covered by the Performance Security;
c. instruct the BAC to ensure that the surety bond issued to contractors as warranty bonds on infrastructure projects contain the specific dates of coverage, specifically the date starting from the time of completion of the project and up to one year to its final acceptance, including the expiration date thereof; and
d. require the MAO to strictly scrutinize the validity period of the performance and warranty securities before effecting payment.

We recommended that Management require the LDRRM Officer to:
a. consider the expected outcomes of PPAs outlined in the updated NDRRMP in the preparation of medium-term and long-term MDRRMP and Annual Investment Plan to ensure coherence and compliance with both national and global development and policy agendas;
b. plan for the inclusion/integration of activities to be funded from the unexpended balances of the LDRRMF into the LDRRMFIP to rationalize the use of the STF;
c. specify clearly in the LDRRMFIP the schedule or period of project implementation to avoid delay in the project execution;
d. incorporate GAD-related PPAs in the LDRRMFIP to ensure that disaster risk reduction measures are gender-responsive;
e. monitor and evaluate the utilization of the LDRRMF based on the PPAs listed in the LDRRMFIP to ensure the full implementation thereof; and
f. regularly review unimplemented PPAs and ascertain the viability of implementation therefrom, otherwise, realign or reprogram for more viable and significant PPAs to maximize the utilization of LDRRMF.

We recommended that Management:
a. require the MENRO to prepare the LGU SWM SCMAR and submit the same within the prescribed period to the Regional Office No. III and SWMD-PDTSS to monitor promptly the status of compliance with R.A. No. 9003;
b. abide with the project schedule to ensure the full implementation of all the SWM priority programs targeted during the year for the benefit of the Municipality and the constituents in general;
c. ensure that garbage collectors are equipped with suitable personal protective equipment or gear to free them from the hazards of handling solid wastes; and
d. instruct the OIC-MENRO in close coordination with the MEO and other concerned departments to: (i) strictly monitor and provide technical assistance to the concerned Barangays to facilitate the operations of EMB-funded Barangay MRFs for an efficient and effective collection and disposal of solid wastes, and as an additional measure to mitigate health and environmental risks. If warranted, initiate necessary steps to process the formal turnover of completed MRFs including the machines located within the territorial jurisdiction of the concerned Barangays to transfer the responsibility in managing and maintaining the properties; (ii) submit a written explanation on the whereabouts of the unaccounted waste shredder machine noted during the ocular inspection for proper disposition by the AT; and (iii) prioritize the installation of three-phase transformer electrical system in the Municipal Sanitary Landfill (MSL) to maximize the use of waste pulverizer and shredder machines and to avoid further deterioration of the same.

We recommended that Management:
a. instruct the MT to undertake the following courses of action:
i. regularly examine the books of accounts of business establishments to determine the truthfulness of the declared gross sales or receipts used in the computation of business taxes paid pursuant to Section 171 of R.A. No. 7160;
ii. assign personnel at the MTO who are well-equipped with the necessary knowledge and training in the examination of books of accounts to enable the said Office to carry on with their mandate efficiently;
iii. tag all the aforesaid suppliers and contractors with underdeclared sales or receipts and be subject to examination of books of accounts to ensure the correctness of taxes, fees, and charges to be collected;
iv. require the supplier with unrenewed business permit to pay the renewal fee and business tax for the period identified and impose possible sanctions for non-compliance with the RRC;
v. coordinate with the ME to identify contractors who have bunkhouses or other structures that may be considered as project offices, which will serve as a basis for the imposing of business tax;
vi. collect business taxes from outside contractors who engaged in business within the Municipality applying the situs of taxation; and
vii. strictly impose the 2% monthly interest on delinquent business taxes; and
viii. require the concerned taxpayers to pay the business tax deficiency of at least ₱1,914,031.15;
b. advise the Designated Business Permit and Licensing Officer (BPLO) to implement the following measures: i. submit a representation to the Sangguniang Bayan (SB) to set up or institutionalize the use of PILAA to arrive at a more realistic basis of business taxes in the absence of the required audited FS or Income Tax Returns (ITRs) or Sworn Statement of Gross Sales or Receipts; ii. refrain from accepting applications for the renewal of business permits that are not based on the documentary requirements like the audited FS or ITRs or Sworn Statements of Gross Sales or Receipts as audited FS, particularly ITRs or Sworn Statements of Gross Sales or Receipts; iii. require the submission of complete documentation of the financial records from taxpayers for the correct assessment of business taxes; and iv. prescribe a standard format of Sworn Statement of Gross Sales or Receipts when applicable and require the business taxpayers to have it duly notarized upon submission; and
c. require the MT and the Designated BPLO to devise measures to validate the declared gross sales or receipts of establishments applying for business permits especially those who are having direct transactions with the Municipality and its Barangays.

We recommended that Management instruct the GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) to:
a. monitor the implementation of the organization-focused GAD PPAs to ensure that the same are implemented as planned to attain GAD’s goals and objectives;
b. attach the documents required under Paragraph 5 of Section 4.0 (C.8) of JMC 2013-01 to facilitate the monitoring and evaluation of the GAD PPAs implemented during the year;
c. observe the deadline for submission of GAD AR to the AT; d. create a centralized GAD Database that would consolidate the information gathered and compiled by all offices to include gender statistics and other relevant sex-disaggregated data as a basis in GAD planning, programming, and policy-making;
e. administer the HGDG test whenever it uses attribution in the budgeting phase and during the AR preparation; and
f. seek help from experts and include HGDG training in the budget to ensure the correctness of the GAD issues identified and the responsiveness of the corresponding GAD PPAs.

We recommended that Management:

instruct the Municipal Treasurer (MT) to (i) intensify collections by undertaking effective revenue collection strategies such as periodic sending of the notice of delinquencies and tax bills by personal or mail service and coordination with barangay officials and national and local offices that have access to the addresses of delinquent taxpayers; 

(ii) avail of all legal and administrative remedies allowed under R.A. No. 7160; 







(iii) submit the RPTAR/certified list of taxpayers and the amount of taxes due and submit a copy of the same to the Municipal Accountant (MA); and 

(iv) maintain close coordination with the Municipal Assessor as regards the newly assessed real properties; and





require the MA to secure the RPTAR/Taxpayer’s Index Card from the MT to come up with the basis for accurate and reliable amounts of RPT/SET Receivables.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the:

MA to draw JEVs taking up the (i) record under the appropriate CIP accounts based on actual completion of projects as shown in the SWA from the contractors validated by the Municipal Engineer (ME) at year-end; 

(ii) prepare adjusting entries to record the accumulated depreciation for the finished projects; and 

(iii) continue to update the PPELC for all property accounts to support the recorded balances of PPE;



Property Custodian/ MT to (i) maintain complete and updated property cards per category of PPE; and 


(ii) report all obsolete and unserviceable PPE in the Inventory and Inspection Report on Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) duly signed by the Head of Accounting Unit, Inspector/Appraisal Committee and approved by Head of Agency or authorized representative, and submit the report to the Disposal Committee for proper disposition;

Municipal Budget Officer (MBO) to recognize the obligation of the construction of infrastructure projects based on progress billings and accomplishment reports submitted by the contractors;



Inventory Committee to (i) conduct a complete physical count of PPE; and 



(ii) prepare/submit the corresponding RPCPPE (with appropriate remarks on the condition and whereabouts of the PPE) to the MAO, GSO, and COA; and

Concerned officials and committees to conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances of the Municipality in compliance with COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

We recommended that LCE in coordination with the HRMO (a) prepare and issue policy guidelines to address the issues on the necessity and propriety of hiring casuals and job orders to limit expenditures to programs/projects where their services are needed; 

(b) hire job order personnel based on necessity and skills/competencies specifically required in the local projects; 




(c) avoid the hiring of job orders whose functions overlap or duplicate those of the regular employees of the Municipality; 



(d) re-evaluate the personnel complements to fill up the vacancies; and 

(e) ensure that all personnel comply with the required biometric scanning and that the accomplishment reports are detailed to reflect the day-to-day accomplishments of the employees.

We recommended that Management require the MDRRMC to:

ensure that the LDRRMF is optimally utilized;




refund the LDRRMF for the amount used to purchase the fire alarm;

properly plan for the inclusion/
integration of activities to be funded from the STF of the LDRRMF into the LDRRMFIP based on an extensive evaluation of the vulnerability of the Municipality to natural or man-made disaster risks to rationalize the use of the STF; and

sustain the current effective responses to disasters and their attendant risks.

We recommended that Management require the MA to (a) revert to the GF the long-outstanding and invalid claims recorded in the books of the Municipality; 




(b) to confirm from the concerned creditors the said payables and require them to submit documents about their claims; and 


(c) in case the creditors fail to support their claims, revert the amount to the Unappropriated Surplus of the GF upon approval of the SB.

We recommended that Management instruct the:

LHB to submit a written explanation on the non-certification of the list of the public HCWs and non-HCWs who were eligible to receive OCA;

concerned official to submit an explanation in the internal arrangement of sharing the OCA to HCWs and Non-HCWs who were not on the official list submitted to DOH and the reason for not including the said personnel to the list submitted if they were indeed eligible to receive the benefits;

concerned officer/employees provide valid proof of the discrepancies noted in the risk classifications of some of the HCWs and Non-HCWs;
HCWs and Non-HCWs concerned to provide valid proofs that they physically reported for work and have provided direct health/support care as well as the actual and detailed accomplishment reports relative thereto; and

MHO or concerned supervisor, being the head of the health facility, to ensure that Accomplishment Reports involved COVID-19 response in line with the prevention, detection, isolation, treatment, rehabilitation, and vaccination strategy.

We recommended the
Management to:
a. require the Municipal Engineer to provide a complete the description and cost segregation of road components for road projects pursuant to Item V of COA Circular No. 2015-008;
b. direct the Municipal Assessor to assist the Municipal Engineer in the assessment of the fair market value of the road lot component of all existing local roads under the jurisdiction of the Municipality;
c. direct the Municipal GSO to prepare and maintain an LRIRRM and conduct Property inventory and reconciliation with the Municipal Accountant between the list of inventory per LRIRRM with those recorded in the RPI; and
d. instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) provide records of CY 2007 to CY 2014 completed infrastructure projects as the basis for recording to PPE accounts and provide appropriate depreciation relative thereto; and (ii) take up the necessary correcting/adjusting entries to recognize completed road projects from previous years and rectify erroneous provision of residual values in depreciating Road Networks account, as Prior Period Adjustment and the corresponding related accounts.

We recommended that
Management instruct the:
a. MDRRM Council to (i) strive for the timely and full implementation of LDRRM-related PPAs to achieve the goals and objective of the fund and the desired benefits; and (ii) include in the preparation of the MDRRMFIP/AIP the PPAs for the entire unexpended balance of prior year LDRRMF to rationalize the use of the Special Trust Fund;
b. Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) and Implementing Offices, the Engineering Office, MDRRMO, MHO and MSWDO, to plan carefully the timetable in the implementation of the DRRM projects and exercise urgency in the procurement process and implementation, especially those under emergency procurement, to immediately address the exigency of the project;
c. Municipal Accountant and Municipal Budget Officer, including MDRRMC, to properly coordinate each other, avoid errors in the preparation of the LDRRMF Utilization Report, create a separate registry for continuing appropriation and LDRRMF-STF for proper monitoring and reporting, and create adjusting entry for overstatement of LDRRMF-STF amounting to ₱416,222.00; and
d. Municipal Treasurer to maintain a separate account with an Authorized Government Depository Bank (AGDB) for the unexpended balance of LDRRMF to secure the STF from comingling with the other TF.

