Coordinate with the barangays on the enforcement of Section 152 (c) of R.A. No. 7160 which requires the submission of barangay clearances by the business establishments before business taxes are paid and permits are issued by the BPLO.

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all supporting documents are complete and attached to the disbursement vouchers before effecting payments;


Require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to post Notice of Award and Notice to Proceed to PhilGEPS within the prescribed period; invite representatives from COA and other observers in various stages of the bidding in accordance with the provisions of Section 13 of the Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184; and  submit copies of contracts to the Auditor’s Office within five working days from the execution and signing thereof; and

Advise the BAC and the Municipal Engineer to ensure strict compliance with DPWH Department Order No. 216 on the submission of photographs with imprinted dates to facilitate verification of the existence and work progress of each project.

We recommended and management agreed to require the: 

Municipal Accountant to (1) draw Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) taking up the (i) reversal of entries made to record the ongoing infrastructure projects without progress billings from the contractors; (ii) transfer of costs of completed projects to the appropriate PPE accounts; (iii) reclassification of the assets acquired for distribution and small tangible items to the appropriate inventory/expense accounts;  (iv) reclassification of procured printers and laptop recorded as Office Equipment to Information and Communication Technology Equipment; (v) reclassification of procured mobile phones recorded as Information and Communication Technology Equipment to Communication Equipment; (vi) dropping of obsolete properties from the books upon disposal; and (2) continue to update the PPELC for all property accounts to support the recorded balances of PPE;


Municipal Treasury and/or Property Custodian to (i) maintain complete and updated property cards per category of PPE; and 



(ii) report all obsolete and unserviceable PPE in the Inventory and Inspection Report on Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) duly signed by the Head of Accounting Unit, Inspector/Appraisal Committee and approved by Head of Agency or authorized representative, and submit the report to the Disposal Committee for proper disposition;

Municipal Budget Officer to recognize the obligation of the construction of infrastructure projects based on progress billings and accomplishment reports submitted by the contractors;



Inventory Committee to (i) conduct complete physical count of PPE; and


(ii) prepare/submit the corresponding RPCPPE (with appropriate remarks on the condition and whereabouts of the PPE) to the Accounting, GSO and COA; and

ensure that all its insurable properties are adequately covered by insurance with the GSIS to obtain maximum protection of the interest of the government and contribute to revenue collection efforts of the National Government as well.

We recommended and management agreed to direct/instruct: 

the Municipal Accountant to (i) transfer the financial assistance from various NGAs from the General Fund and Special Education Fund to the Trust Fund books in accordance with existing accounting policy;

 (ii) trace the records/documents relative to the unaccounted balances, reconcile the same, and remit the correct balance to the source agencies; 

(iii) coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer for the return of unused funds to the source agencies (SAs) or to the National Treasury, as the case may be; 

(iv) draw adjusting/ correcting entries for the procurement of various assets; and 



(v) scrutinize the completeness of supporting documents of claims before releasing the same for payment and prior to the recording of the transactions in the books of accounts;

the Municipal Treasurer to draw a check for the remittance of unutilized amount of all completed projects including trust collections for ante-mortem and slaughterhouse fees after proper reconciliation/analysis done by the Accounting Office; and 

the BAC and TWG to adhere to the documentary requirements in all stages of the bidding processes and submit to the Audit Team the required documents for infrastructure projects implemented in CY 2018.

We recommended and management agreed to advice the:

Local School Board to continue to maximize the utilization of SEF and implement programs and projects, especially the construction/ improvements of school buildings and classrooms to ensure the provision of facilities conducive for learning;

Municipal Accountant to (i) scrutinize the completeness of supporting documents of claims before releasing the same for payment; and (ii) request for the replacement of invalid sales invoices and collection receipts issued by the supplier of school uniforms and supplies; 




Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to comply strictly with the provisions of R.A. No. 9184 and its Revised IRR particularly on (i) invitation of observers on all stages of procurement; and 




(ii) imposition of warranty security on the procurement goods; 

Municipal Engineer to require the contractor concerned to undertake immediate repair on the Home Economics Buildings constructed at San Lorenzo and Sta. Rita Elementary Schools; and submit complete documentation on the payment of infrastructure projects for the construction and repairs of school buildings and facilities; and

Recipients of the load allowance to provide certification from DepEd that they are authorized to receive the same; including the authorized amount and provide justification regarding the duplication of supporting documents for two separate claims.

We recommended and management agreed to:

Adhere to the required composition of the GAD Focal Point System and the creation of GFPS Technical Working Group (TWG) to institutionalize gender mainstreaming; 

Gather GAD information such as gender statistics and sex-disaggregated data to serve as inputs for planning, budgeting, programming and policy formulation for the setting up and maintenance of GAD database; 

Prioritize measures on the development and updating of the GAD Code; 



Ensure the timely submission of GAD Plan and Budget to the DILG and PPDO; 



Create a Monitoring and Evaluation Team to take responsibility of assessing the status of PPAs in relation to the plan and existing GAD policy; and 

Ensure that GAD Accomplishment Report is supported with (i) a brief summary of the reported program or project; 
(ii) copies of reported policy issuances; and 

(iii) results of HGDG tests to provide basis of measuring the performance of the LGU in terms of all the requirements of the PCW-DILG-DBM and NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-01 dated July 18, 2013.

We recommended and management agreed to consider the following courses of actions:

Advise the Local School Board to develop a standard and set of guidelines for the effective and efficient implementation of the Supplemental Feeding Program;

